description.text:
This is a remix of the super Bullzeye Clock by Zarlor. I have re-designed it to be 1.5 times larger and added a ratchet on the string pulley for easy winding. My clock runs for about 8 hours and uses a 1.7Kg weight. I used lead shot. All the steel rods are 2mm the four main ones for the gears are 43mm long. The rod in the string gear is glued into the gear. The other three gear assemblies spin freely on their rods. The rods for the pendulum and the hands are sized to suit. I used 15mm x 3mm cap screws to hold the frame halves together which allows for easy disassembly. I used powered graphite as a lubricant to get things running freely. The weight cord is nylon 75lb fishing line but any strong cord would do. It's wrapped around the pulley about 3 1/2 times, just enough to stop it slipping. The one way ratchet allows for easy winding. Thanks to Goofy for the idea for that. There's a video of the clock running here :-

https://youtu.be/l88Bo01-u7I

description.text: After building a spinner or two I realized that I wasn't using the 22mm bearings on the spinner arms for anything more than weight. Additionally, it seemed like I could get a bit more inertia with a heavier weight. I had some Indium casting alloy around, McMaster Carr PN88635K2. It has about the same density as bronze. It melts at 117F, and so I use hot water to melt it and then I can use it for casting parts. There are different melt points available, so if you are concerned this would be exposed to temperatures higher than 117F in the wild, then maybe select a higher melt point. These alloys all contain some lead also, and I am not sure about the potential health effects from the lead in the alloy. I made some casts with this, and it worked just fine except that this metal is unique in that it expands when cooled rather than contracts. That makes it a pain to get out of the mold. I thought about adding some draft to the sides to help this, but then I don't think it would hold as tightly in the space on the spinner. Also, be sure to cool the part completely before you open the mold or it will just spill out. I put my cast part in the mold (still clamped) into a bowl of ice water for about 15 minutes to make sure. The cast Indium parts from this mold weighed 22grams, and the bearings intended for the spinner only weighed 10g. If this is too heavy the mold cavity could be modified to use less material. Also, I bought some casting resin and some iron filler and next I am going to try making some parts with this filled resin. I am not sure how heavy these parts will be. I'll try to update this post when I get there. Not sure how to publish the native files here, so if anyone wants the fusion360 native files let me know how to do this.

description.header: Pasos para el Armado y Configuraciones de Impresión
description.text:
Pasos para el armado de un ArmPO:

Estos son los archivos correspondientes a un Armpo para un brazo derecho, por eso el prefijo "R_" en los nombres de cada parte.

  • Termoformar el R_triceps y la R_base del antebrazo según el muñón del usuario.

  • Presentar la R_base y la R_hand encastrando los relieves de la R_hand con las perforaciones de la R_base.

  • Ensamblar R_hand (la palma) con los R_fingerplate (dedos) y los finger_flexibles.

  • Colocar los hilos a los dedos R_fingerplate pasando por la palma R_hand.

  • Unir R_base termoformada y R_triceps usando los Flexible_ring_elbow y los Pins.

  • Colocar los hilos al antebrazo.

  • Unir la R_base y el antebrazo encastrando correspondientemente y pegándolos. Encastrar y pegar el lock, uniendo los extremos de la R_base.

  • Tensionar los hilos con los Tensioners. Usar un Tensioners para el pulgar y el otro para los demás dedos.

  • Termoformar el Cover y unir el antebrazo con los Flexible_rings.
Sistema de sujeción: codera y velcro
Detalles

  • El largo de la codera es 9cm más el largo del muñón del usuario.

  • La circunferencia de la codera es la circunferencia más grande entre la del brazo y la del antebrazo del usuario.

  • El neopreno que va dentro de la codera mide 7cm por 2cm menos que la circunferencia de la codera.

  • La tela lleva 1,5cm de ruedo en ambos bordes.

  • De izquierda a derecha, el largo de cada correa de velcro lleva 7cm de velcro áspero, velcro suave igual de largo que la circunferencia de la codera, y 4cm de correa al final para la hebilla.
Pasos

  • Cubrir los interiores del antebrazo (Cover y R_base) y el interior de R_triceps con material espumoso.

  • Hacer dos cortes en la codera que coinciden con las aberturas de R_triceps.

  • Pasar una correa de velcro a través de las aberturas en Cover y R_base y abrocharla.

  • Pasar otra correa de velcro a través de las aberturas en R_triceps y abrocharla.
Configuraciones de impresión
Las siguientes piezas son impresas con una impresora RepRap Prusa i3 con volumen de impresión de 230x400x250 mm.

R_base y R_triceps:

Se imprimen con 0.2 mm de altura de capa con 70% de relleno(tipo rejilla), con ángulos de 90 y 0. Con una velocidad de impresión de 60 mm/s (dependiendo de la impresora).

Cover:
Se imprime con 0.2 mm de altura de capa y con 70% de relleno (tipo rejilla), con ángulos de 90 y 0. Con una velocidad de impresión de 60 mm/s (dependiendo de la impresora).

Las siguientes piezas son impresas con una impresora RepRap Prusa i3 o FlashForge Creator Dual. Estas permiten imprimir PLA y filamento flexible.

Pins, Tensioners, Lock, y Tensioner Block:
Se imprimen con 0.2 mm de altura de capa y con 70% de relleno (tipo rejilla), con ángulos de 90 y 0. Con una velocidad de impresión de 60 mm/s.

Las siguientes piezas son impresas con filamento flexible.

Flexible_rings y flexible_ring_elbow:
Se imprime con 0.2 mm de altura de capa y con 70% de relleno (tipo rejilla), con ángulos de 90 y 0. Con una velocidad de impresión de 30 mm/s. (Esta velocidad depende del tipo de flexible y el tipo de impresora usada)

El resto de las partes son impresas con las configuraciones recomendadas para una Flexyhand estándar.

ArmPo Assembly instructions

These are the files corresponding to an Armpo for a right arm, hence the prefix "R_" in the names of each part.

  • Thermoform R_triceps and R_base of the forearm according to the size of the users limb.

  • Place the R_base and the R_hand embedding the reliefs of the R_hand with the perforations of the R_base.

  • Standard flexy hand assembly for R_hand with the fingers R_fingerplate and the finger_flexibles.

  • Standard flexy hand stringing for R_hand.

  • Fix the thermoformed R_base to R_triceps using the Flexible_rings_elbow and the Pins.

  • String through the forearm.

  • Join the R_base and the forearm by fitting and sticking them together. Insert and stick the lock, joining the ends of the R_base.

  • Tense the strings using the Tensioners. Use one Tensioners for the thumb and the other one for the remaining fingers

  • Thermoform the Cover and fix it to the forearm with the Flexible_rings
Clamping system: elbow pad and velcro
Details

  • The elbow pad’s length is 9cm plus the length of the user’s stump.

  • The circumference of the elbow pad is the longer circumference between the arm and forearm of the user.

  • The neoprene that goes inside the elbow pad is 7cm by 2cm less than the elbow pad’s circumference.

  • The cloth has 1.5cm of rolled fabric in both borders.

  • From left to right, the length of each velcro strap is 7cm of rough velcro, soft velcro equal to the elbow pad’s circumference, and 4cm of strap in the end for the buckle.
Instructions for the elbow pad and velcro:

  • Cover the insides of the forearm (Cover and R_base) and the insides of R_triceps with foamy material.

  • Cut two slits in the elbow pad that coincide with the gaps in R_triceps.

  • Pass a velcro strap through the gaps in Cover and R_base and fasten it.

  • Pass another velcro strap through the gaps in R_triceps and fasten it.

title: Autolevel Z-probe mount and arm for Velleman K8200 / 3Drag (5g servo)

description.text:
Overview

Designed to fit a microservo (5g) and to position the probe (microswitch) closely to the hotend (E3D v6 on my mount in particular).

Cutout for servo's arm (the small OEM one) is slightly undersized and may require enlargening after printing (or trimming the arm).

Assembly

To assemble, you'll additionally need:

  • M5x15 screw, M5 washer and square M5 nut (for attaching mount to printer)
  • M2x12 screw and M2 nut (for attaching servo to mount)
  • 2x M3x12 screw and 2x M3 nut (for attaching microswitch to arm)

Wiring

For original K8200 controller

Plug probe's microswitch to Z endstop socket.
Wire servo to extension connector on the controller board:

  • Black (or brown) -> GND
  • Red -> 5V
  • Yellow -> SS pin

Tips (see picture):

  • I've used GND pin already for a fan so I've soldered second header on the back of the board
  • You can use old PC connectors for nicer management of wires

For other controllers

Figure it out yourself. Should be simpler.

Configuration

To enable automatic bed leveling/trimming, you'll need Marlin in version 1.0.2 or newer (get it from here), official K8200 software doesn't support this feature.

For general tips and hints I recommend this great video by Thomas Sanladerer. There are however differences in software used - see in 'Probe Z-distance calibration' section.

Copy your old configuration

Best option is to open your current configuration.h and the new one side-by-side and copy corresponding values, as the structure of the file has changed and new features that we'll use were added.

Instead of hard-coding motherboard type value (77) you can use following code:

#define MOTHERBOARD BOARD_3DRAG

Enable autoleveling

First, find and uncomment line:

#define ENABLE_AUTO_BED_LEVELING

Then, set up rectangle in which to probe, my recommended values (big margin for glass clamps):

#define LEFT_PROBE_BED_POSITION 40
#define RIGHT_PROBE_BED_POSITION 160
#define BACK_PROBE_BED_POSITION 160
#define FRONT_PROBE_BED_POSITION 40

Lastly, set up position of probe relative to nozzle. X and Y offsets can be rough estimates, while Z offset will be fine-adjusted further on (see 'Probe Z-distance calibration' section).
Values below are for E3Dv6 hotend mounted on my bracket and servo mount placed roughly 30mm from said bracket (see picture).

#define X_PROBE_OFFSET_FROM_EXTRUDER -35 // X_probe > X_nozzle
#define Y_PROBE_OFFSET_FROM_EXTRUDER 4 // Y_probe < Y_nozzle
#define Z_PROBE_OFFSET_FROM_EXTRUDER -50 // Not calibrated! Don't print with this value!

WARNING! Don't print with these settings, Z offset requires further tuning!

Enable servo support

In pins.h add following code to line 736:

#if MB(3DRAG)
  #define SERVO0_PIN 53
#endif

This will enable servo support of SS pin of extension connector on the board.

In configuration.h, find 'R/C SERVO support' section and uncomment and adjust following lines:

#define NUM_SERVOS 1
#define SERVO_ENDSTOPS {-1, -1, 0}
#define SERVO_ENDSTOP_ANGLES {0,0, 0,0, 85,170}

To check whether servo angles are correct (85 for extended and 170 for retracted) you can use following G-code:

M280 P0 S85; extend the arm
M280 P0 S170; retract the arm

Additionally, to avoid weird jerky movements of the arm (Marlin's bug?), uncomment line 427 in configuration.h:

#define PROBE_SERVO_DEACTIVATION_DELAY 300

Save, compile and upload

Self-explanatory.

Probe Z-distance calibration

General procedure is the same as in Thomas Sanladerer's video, but due to slight differences in G-code there are minor differences.

  • Start up the printer
  • Connect with your host software
  • Home all axes (Z must be last one)
  • Issue Z-probe G-code:
    G29
  • Home X&Y axes
  • Go to middle of your printbed
  • Put a piece of paper on the printbed under hotend
  • SLOWLY, IN SMALL STEPS lower your hotend until it just slightly holds the paper against printbed.
    • Write down by how much you lowered your hotend! Example: 14.2
    • You can also read current position from output of M114 command and subtract it from initial value after calibration (here: 50)
  • Open configuration.h once again and set value of probe's Z-offset:
    #define Z_PROBE_OFFSET_FROM_EXTRUDER 14.2
  • Save, compile and upload once again

Slicer configuration

In custom G-code section (for Slic3r it's in 'Printer Settings') add G29 just after G28.

This is a simple mold to make a foot for the 3Dator

Step 0 - Print the mold

Important: Use at least 20% infill and at least 6 top layers with 0.1mm layer height.

Try to print as clean as you can, since this effects the result 1:1.

Step 1 - Prepare the mold

Make sure that the print is clean and has no strings, since everything wrong with the mold gets transfered to the Foot.

In my experience the mold doesn't need mold release, since pla or petg is slippery enough.

Step 2 - Mix the silicone

Depending on your choice of silicone mix it accordingly to the instructions. You will need about 6-7g per foot (x4 if you want to fill all 4 molds).

Tipp:

  • Transfer the mixed silicone to a second container and mix it again, this makes sure that its really mixed
  • I used a silicone with a hardnes of around 20 Shore. Harder silicones dont dampen the vibrations as much.
Step 3 - Pour the silicone in all molds

Simply pour the silicone into the mold. And wait for it to harden

Step 4 - Wait for the silicone to cure

Wait for the silicone to cure. It is better to wait longer since the hardened silicone has to be strong enough to be pulled out of the mold.

This pen body was designed to add an interesting geometric flair to an otherwise ordinary pen.

The part was designed to fit the ink refill from the Bic Cristal pens, which can be found here: http://amzn.to/2lndAQm

Notes:

I printed mine using Simplify3D software and my Dremel Idea Builder, using PLA filament and printing in High detail with 100% infill (solid).

The software will likely try to add support material on the inside where the ink will go. This would be too hard to remove and you can get by without it. Instead, I used manually-added supports on each end, and along the outside to keep the pen from rolling as it was being printed.

The pen was designed in Fusion 360. First the ink refill was measured and modeled, and then the pen body was modeled around it. Before making the larger model, I created a few "pen tip" test pieces with different hole diameters to find the best size hole for the ink to fit in.

description.text:
A simple wooden stand designed to tilt your tablet or laptop into a more ergonomic viewing position. 
The design uses standard struts that can be scaled to fit your tablet or laptop. 
The included SVG template prints the struts needed to produce a 15in laptop stand & an iPad stand.

Use 3.6mm wood to print this template; the complete template requires an 11in x 17in board. Once the structs are cut, fit them together to create your stand. For a 15in Laptop: Use the longest set of struts on the outside and the midsize struts on the inside. Space the struts evenly along the notched support with the longest struts on each end. For an iPad (or similar tablet): Use the shortest set of struts. Fit the struts at the far ends of the supports. For tablets / laptops which may require more support, use more struts spaced evenly along the notched support. The design has only been tested with a 2011 15in Macbook pro and an iPad. Heavier laptops or larger tablets may require additional supports or modified struct lengths. When modifying the strut lengths, make sure the holes for the supports don't change shape or size! The included images show multiple strut configurationsÃÂ¢Ã¢ÂÂ¬Ã¢ÂÂ test different combinations to see which works best for your device. The Notch supports should fit tightly into the struts; Depending on your tools & the type of wood you use it may be necessary to modify the width of the notches to ensure a tight fit.If things turn out wobbly with your configuration out, just add glue!

comments.text:
I had a couple of problems cutting this. Initially I did a test run on a piece of scrap 3.2mm MDF. It was a tight fit, but could be assembled. However, the parts seemed way too small to hold a laptop (longest strut was only 185mm, and notches in the support was 2.6mm).
I decided to try and cut it in 4mm MDF, and simply scaled everything by 154% (factor from 2.6mm notch to desired 4mm notch). I did not adjust for kerf or anything, and this one came out good. One of the supports did not fit, however, so I recut the one that did. The longest struts are sticking out maybe 15-20mm on the back of my 13" laptop, but works fine.
